SECTION 1 — CORE ICT CONCEPTS
Fair Value Gap (FVG) / BISI / SIBI
A 3-candle inefficiency where price moves too fast, leaving a gap. Bullish FVG (BISI = Buy Side Imbalance Sell Side
Inefficiency) forms when candle 1 high is below candle 3 low. Bearish FVG (SIBI) is the opposite. Price consistently
returns to fill these gaps.
KEY RULE: Enter at CE of FVG. Bullish = support. Bearish = resistance. Bodies must close inside
for invalidation.
Inversion Fair Value Gap (IFVG)
When price completely breaks through a FVG (bodies close outside it), the FVG inverts. A bullish FVG that gets
broken becomes a bearish IFVG and vice versa. These are powerful re-entry and continuation signals.
KEY RULE: Wait for displacement candle to close outside FVG. Then trade back INTO it from the
new direction.
1st Presented FVG
The very FIRST Fair Value Gap that forms after price crosses a key level (like a liquidity pool or opening range). ICT
considers this the highest probability FVG because it represents the initial algorithmic commitment to a new direction.
KEY RULE: After liquidity is taken, the FIRST FVG that forms in the new direction = highest
probability entry. Do not skip it for a 'better' one.
Order Block (OB)
The last opposing candle BEFORE a strong impulsive move. Bullish OB = last down-close candle before a rally.
Bearish OB = last up-close candle before a drop. Enter at the OPEN of the order block candle.
KEY RULE: Enter at opening price of OB candle. Stop loss beyond the wick. Invalidated when a
body closes through it.
Breaker Block
An Order Block that FAILS — price breaks through it, then comes BACK to it from the other side. The failed bullish OB
becomes a bearish Breaker. The failed bearish OB becomes a bullish Breaker. More powerful than regular OB
because trapped traders are squeezed.
KEY RULE: Only trade Breakers in the direction of the break. The original swing high/low that was
violated is the entry zone.
Mitigation Block
After a loss move, price retraces back to the last opposing candle (where the original move began) to 'mitigate' trapped
orders. Similar to OB but specifically in context of drawdown recovery.
KEY RULE: Used for re-entry after a losing trade. Price returns to where it started the losing move
— that is your mitigation block entry.
Consequent Encroachment (CE)
The exact 50% midpoint of ANY range — FVG, Order Block, wick, gap, or suspension block. The single most
important level inside any array. Candle BODIES respecting CE confirms the setup is valid.
KEY RULE: Wicks CAN violate CE. BODIES must stay on correct side. If body closes past CE, exit
or reduce position.
Suspension Block
A special candle containing Volume Imbalance at BOTH top AND bottom — creating a 'suspended' zone. The
midpoint CE is critical. Bodies above CE = bullish. Bodies below CE = bearish.
KEY RULE: Often forms on daily charts as key turning points. Mark CE carefully. It acts as both
support and resistance within the block.
Liquidity Pools (BSL / SSL)
Buy Side Liquidity (BSL) = equal highs where retail stop losses cluster above. Sell Side Liquidity (SSL) = equal lows
with stops below. ICT's core belief: algorithms always target liquidity before reversing.
KEY RULE: Mark ALL relative equal highs and lows. The algorithm WILL sweep them. This sweep =
your entry signal.
Volume Imbalance (VI)
A 2-candle gap: one candle's CLOSE and the next candle's OPEN don't overlap. Measured to exact ticks/quarters.
Price returns to fill. The 50% midpoint is most important reaction level.
KEY RULE: Mark exact close-to-open gap. 50% level = CE. Strongest when it aligns with other PD
arrays.
Rejection Block
A candle with an extremely long wick that represents aggressive rejection of a price level. The wick itself acts as a gap
— ICT treats it identically to a FVG. Grade the wick like a gap using Fibonacci.
KEY RULE: Draw fib from wick low to wick high (or vice versa). CE = 50% of wick. Trade back into
the wick expecting rejection at CE.
Propulsion Block
A series of consecutive same-direction candles that 'propel' price. When price returns to this zone, it acts as an order
block. Usually 3+ up-close candles in a row (bullish propulsion) or down-close candles (bearish).
KEY RULE: Mark the extreme candle of the propulsion series as entry. Bodies must stay within the
propulsion zone for it to remain valid.
Vacuum Block
A large gap in price that acts like a vacuum — price gets 'sucked' through it rapidly with almost no resistance. Forms
during news events or extreme volatility. No reliable PD arrays exist inside a vacuum block.
KEY RULE: Do NOT trade inside a vacuum block. Wait for price to exit the vacuum and find the next
PD array.
SMT Divergence
When two correlated instruments (NQ vs ES, or EUR/USD vs GBP/USD) make different highs or lows at the same
time. SMT = Smart Money Technique. Divergence indicates institutional disagreement = likely reversal.
KEY RULE: SMT is a QUALIFIER only. It confirms other setups but is NOT a standalone entry
signal. NQ higher high + ES lower high = bearish SMT.
