SECTION 3 — ICT TRADING MODELS
ICT Silver Bullet
A TIME-BASED model that works during specific 20-minute windows. The setup requires a Fair Value Gap to form
DURING the macro window, then enter on the retracement into that FVG.
• Time windows: 3:00-4:00 AM (London), 10:00-11:00 AM (NY AM), 2:00-3:00 PM (NY PM)
• Wait for price to SWEEP a liquidity level (equal highs or lows)
• After the sweep, a FVG must form in the OPPOSITE direction
• Enter inside that FVG during the macro window
• Target: opposite liquidity pool (equal lows if short, equal highs if long)
• Stop: beyond the wick that swept liquidity
Turtle Soup (Short & Long)
Price runs ABOVE a previous swing high (buy side liquidity) or BELOW a previous swing low (sell side liquidity) by a
few ticks, trapping breakout traders, then immediately reverses. This fake breakout IS the entry.
• Identify swing high with equal/relative equal highs (buy side pool)
• Wait for price to RUN above those highs by 1-5 ticks
• Look for immediate bearish rejection — a down-close candle forms
• Enter short at or inside the first FVG that forms after the sweep
• Stop: just above the new high made during the turtle soup
• Target: sell side liquidity below (equal lows)
• Deferred Entry: if you miss the first entry, wait for price to retrace to a Rejection Block
AMD — Accumulation, Manipulation, Distribution
ICT's core market cycle theory. Every significant price move has 3 phases. Understanding which phase you're in
determines your trade direction.
• ACCUMULATION: Price consolidates in a tight range. Smart money building positions. Do not trade.
• MANIPULATION (Judas Swing): Price spikes FALSE direction to trap retail. This is the ENTRY signal.
• DISTRIBUTION: Price runs in the TRUE direction. This is where you hold for targets.
• Example: Market opens, drops (manipulation/Judas swing), then rallies all day (distribution up)
• The morning session often shows AMD in real time — the Judas Swing happens at 9:30-10:00 AM
Market Maker Buy Model (MMBM)
A bullish delivery pattern. Price first takes out SELL SIDE liquidity (runs stops below lows), then aggressively rallies to
take out BUY SIDE liquidity (runs highs). The entry is after the sell side is taken.
• Step 1: Identify sell side liquidity pool below (equal lows)
• Step 2: Wait for price to SWEEP that sell side (run below the lows)
• Step 3: Look for first bullish FVG or Order Block after the sweep
• Step 4: Enter long inside the FVG/OB
• Target: buy side liquidity above (equal highs)
• Stop: below the lowest wick of the sell side sweep
Market Maker Sell Model (MMSM)
A bearish delivery pattern (opposite of MMBM). Price first takes out BUY SIDE liquidity (runs highs), then aggressively
drops to take SELL SIDE liquidity (runs lows). Entry is after the buy side is taken.
• Step 1: Identify buy side liquidity pool above (equal highs, ATH, etc.)
• Step 2: Wait for price to SWEEP that buy side (run above the highs)
• Step 3: Look for first bearish FVG or bearish Order Block after the sweep
• Step 4: Enter short inside the FVG/OB
• Target: sell side liquidity below (equal lows)
• Stop: above the wick high of the buy side sweep
ICT Venom Model
A specific ICT intraday model introduced in 2025. Uses the pre-session and first hour of trading. Look for a CISD
(Change In State of Delivery) in the pre-market, then trade the opening range accordingly.
• Scan pre-market (7:00-9:30 AM) for CISD — 3 consecutive candles that change direction
• Mark the high and low of the pre-session range
• At 9:30 open: if bullish CISD, look for buy setups in lower half of pre-session range
• At 9:30 open: if bearish CISD, look for short setups in upper half of pre-session range
• Best used with 1st Presented FVG logic in the 9:50-10:10 macro
One Shot One Kill (OSOK)
ICT's philosophy for patient, high-conviction trading. Only ONE trade per session, perfectly executed at the most ideal
setup. Quality over quantity. A true sniper approach.
• Only enter when ALL conditions align: correct session, right time of day, clear liquidity target, valid PD array
• If you are not 80%+ confident — DO NOT ENTER
• One trade per day is sufficient if executed correctly
• Use the first hours range + 1st Presented FVG for highest probability
• Target must be at least 3:1 risk/reward
• After taking a trade (win or loss), close charts for the day
SECTION 4 — ADVANCED PD ARRAYS
Balanced Price Range (BPR)
When a Bullish FVG and a Bearish FVG OVERLAP on the chart — the overlapping zone is called a Balanced Price
Range. This overlap is an extremely high-probability zone because BOTH buy and sell side inefficiencies converge
there. Price respects it powerfully.
CISD — Change In State of Delivery
Three consecutive candles that shift direction. Used to identify when the algorithm has changed its bias. Bullish CISD
= 3 up-close candles (last down-close candle before them = bearish OB turned bullish). Bearish CISD = 3 down-close
candles.
Reaper PD Array
ICT's advanced concept introduced in 2023. A specific combination of liquidity sweep + FVG + Order Block that forms
a highly specific reversal pattern. Named for its 'harvesting' of retail stops.
Grey Pools
Institutional order flow zones that are not visible on standard charts. ICT teaches identifying areas where large
institutional orders cluster based on previous price action patterns. Used for higher timeframe analysis.
Breakaway Gap
A gap that forms OUTSIDE a previous range — signaling a true breakout rather than manipulation. Breakaway gaps
often stay OPEN (don't fill) because they represent genuine institutional commitment. Do NOT fade them.
Opening Range Gap (ORG)
Gap between previous day settlement and today's 9:30 open. Has a high, a low, and a CE (midpoint). Price oscillates
around ORG all day. Filling the ORG is a common intraday draw on liquidity.
New Day Opening Gap (NDOG)
Gap between the electronic session open (midnight) and the previous day's close. Smaller than ORG but significant
for pre-market and overnight traders. Price respects NDOG levels throughout the day.
Midnight Opening Range
The range that forms from midnight to 1:00 AM EST (electronic trading open). ICT introduced this as a key reference
frame in 2025. Price frequently returns to the midnight opening range high/low during the NY session.
New Week Opening Gap (NWOG)
Gap between Friday close and Monday open. Major weekly draw on liquidity. Expect price to visit BOTH the high and
low of the NWOG during the trading week.
Central Bank Dealers Range (CBDR)
The range formed between 2:00 PM and 8:00 PM EST (New York close to European open). This range represents
institutional positioning. A break of the CBDR high or low often signals the direction for the London session.
Friday Asian Range
The Asian session range on Fridays is often targeted by the Monday morning move. Mark Friday's Asian high and low.
Monday often runs one side before reversing.
SECTION 5 — OPENING GAP THEORY (Complete)
ICT's Opening Range Gap theory is one of his most practical and repeatable concepts. Every gap creates actionable
levels. Here is the complete hierarchy:
GAP TYPE WHEN IT FORMS HIGH PROBABILITY TRADE
Midnight Gap (NDOG) Midnight EST open vs prev close Price returns to fill or respect CE during NY
New Week Gap (NWOG) Monday open vs Friday close Visit both high AND low during the week
RTH Opening Range Gap 9:30 AM vs previous settlement CE respected multiple times during the day
CBDR 2:00 PM – 8:00 PM EST range Break of CBDR = direction for London session
Asian Range 6:00 PM – midnight EST London often runs the opposite side of Asian range
Breakaway Gap Outside previous range DO NOT fade — trade in direction of break
Volume Imbalance Candle close to next open gap Price fills to CE (50%) of the imbalance
HOW TO USE FIRST HOUR RANGE
When you have NO initial bias, ICT teaches using the First Hour Trading Range (9:30-10:30 AM) as your framework:
• Mark the HIGHEST high and LOWEST low of the first hour (9:30 to 10:30 AM)
• Calculate 8ths / gradient levels on this range using Fibonacci tool
• If BULLISH: focus on the UPPER half of the range for entries
• If BEARISH: focus on the LOWER half of the range for entries
• Look for FVGs and Order Blocks inside these gradient levels
• The gradient levels act like mini support/resistance — bodies respect them
• When uncertain of direction: wait for 10:00 AM news, then use first hour range to frame your trade
SECTION 6 — MARKET MAKER MODELS DETAIL
Market Maker Buy Model — Step by Step
1 — Accumulation
Price consolidates in a range. Smart money accumulates longs quietly. Retail sees
a 'boring' market. DO NOT TRADE during accumulation.
2 — Manipulation
(Judas Swing Down)
Price drops BELOW the accumulation low, triggering retail stop losses and
attracting new shorts. This is the FAKE move. Smart money is buying this drop.
3 — Distribution
(Rally)
Price aggressively rallies, taking out all the equal highs above. All the shorts get
squeezed. This is where you ride the trend.
Entry Zone
Enter LONG when the Judas Swing drops below accumulation low AND price
shows first bullish FVG or OB on the 1-minute chart during a macro window.
Market Maker Sell Model — Step by Step
1 — Accumulation
Price consolidates. Smart money quietly building SHORT positions while retail
sees ranging market.
2 — Manipulation
(Judas Swing Up)
Price spikes ABOVE the accumulation high, trapping retail breakout buyers and
clearing stops above. Smart money is SELLING this rally.
3 — Distribution
(Drop)
Price aggressively falls, sweeping sell side liquidity pools below. Breakout buyers
get stopped out. This is the sustained move.
Entry Zone
Enter SHORT when Judas Swing runs above accumulation high AND price shows
first bearish FVG or OB on 1-minute chart during macro window.
SECTION 7 — RISK MANAGEMENT & POSITION SIZING
ICT's Core Risk Rules
• Never risk more than 1-2% of account per trade
• Start with ONE MICRO CONTRACT per trade while learning
• Micro S&P; (MES) = $5 per handle | Micro NASDAQ (MNQ) = $2 per point
• Goal for beginners: $50/day with 1 micro = $1,000/month over 20 trading days
• After 3 consecutive losses, STOP trading for the day — no exceptions
• Never add to a losing position without a clear algorithmic re-entry signal
• Never use more than 3 micros until you have 3 profitable months consistently
• Target 6% per month on your account — compounding builds wealth
• Always use limit orders for entries — NEVER market orders into a position
• If your internet drops or something unexpected happens — MARKET ORDER OUT immediately
Stop Loss Placement Rules
• For longs: Stop BELOW the wick low of the liquidity sweep (the Judas Swing low)
• For shorts: Stop ABOVE the wick high of the liquidity sweep
• NEVER place stop inside a wick — wicks are designed to sweep stops
• After first partial taken: move stop to breakeven
• After second partial taken: move stop to first target level
• Do NOT widen your stop after entry — if it's wrong it's wrong
• ICT's rule: if your stop would be hit on a 'normal' candle, your stop is too tight
Partial Profit Taking Rules
• First partial (1/3): at first liquidity pool target
• Second partial (1/3): at Opening Range Gap high/low
• Final (1/3): at major daily draw (NWOG, daily FVG, prev high/low)
• "You never go wrong taking profits" — ICT's rule
• If trade is uncomfortable and approaching target: MARKET ORDER — take the profit
• Never let a winning trade turn into a loss — trail stop aggressively after 2nd partial
SECTION 8 — COMPLETE TRADE ENTRY CHECKLIST
STEP 1 — DAILY CHART BIAS (Do This Night Before)
• Open daily chart — identify nearest Suspension Block or FVG
• Mark the Consequent Encroachment (CE = midpoint) of that level
• Price below CE = BEARISH bias | Price above CE = BULLISH bias
• Mark nearest Buy Side Liquidity (equal highs above)
• Mark nearest Sell Side Liquidity (equal lows below)
• Determine: which pool is the PRIMARY draw for tomorrow?
• Mark the New Week Opening Gap high and low (if applicable)
• Check: is there a NY Lunch FVG from yesterday to carry forward?
STEP 2 — MORNING PREPARATION (Before 9:00 AM)
• Mark yesterday's settlement price (RTH close at 4:00 PM)
• After 9:30 open: mark today's Opening Range Gap (ORG)
• Check Midnight Opening Gap levels
• Mark New Day Opening Gap (NDOG) if using pre-market
• Identify the premium half vs discount half of day's range so far
• Set price alerts at key levels — do not watch chart continuously
• Review macro windows: know EXACTLY when 9:50, 10:10, 1:50, 2:50 PM are
STEP 3 — OPENING RANGE OBSERVATION (9:30–9:50 AM)
• Do NOT trade the first 20 minutes — observe only
• Watch for the Judas Swing direction
• Note where the first FVG formed on 1-minute chart
• Is price in PREMIUM (upper half ORG) or DISCOUNT (lower half)?
• Premium = look for SHORTS only | Discount = look for LONGS only
• What is the 1st Presented FVG after 9:30? Mark it.
STEP 4 — ENTRY EXECUTION (9:50 AM onwards)
• Wait for macro window to begin (9:50 AM earliest)
• Price must reach a valid PD Array (FVG / OB / IFVG / Rejection Block)
• Liquidity MUST be taken BEFORE your entry zone
• Check SMT divergence with correlated market for confirmation
• Candle BODIES must respect your CE level — wicks don't count
• Enter with LIMIT ORDER at CE of FVG or at OB open price
• Stop loss: BEYOND the wick of the liquidity sweep
• Target identified: minimum 2:1 risk/reward, ideally 3:1 or more
STEP 5 — TRADE MANAGEMENT
• Watch the candlestick behavior — it tells you if the trade is working
• Fast, long-bodied candles away from entry = GOOD
• Too many small candles inside FVG = WARNING — consider taking partial
• At first target: take 1/3 off, move stop to breakeven
• At second target: take 1/3 off, move stop to first target level
• NEVER trade during NY Lunch (12:00–1:30 PM)
• If trade reaches 3rd target or EOD: close remaining position
• Log the trade in journal IMMEDIATELY after closing
SECTION 9 — NY LUNCH REVERSAL SETUP
ICT's advanced PD Array specifically taught for 2026. Uses the previous day's NY Lunch session to predict the next
day's high or low.
1 On the PREVIOUS day, mark the NY Lunch window: 12:00 PM to 1:30 PM
2 Find WHERE liquidity was taken near the END of that lunch window
3 Find the FVG that formed RIGHT BEFORE that liquidity was swept
4 Extend those EXACT price levels forward to the NEXT day as a rectangle
5 If price trades UP into those levels the next day = HIGH PROBABILITY SHORT
6 If price trades DOWN into those levels = HIGH PROBABILITY LONG
7 Candle bodies must stay on correct side of the zone's CE level
8 Target: the opposite major liquidity pool for the day
