SECTION 10 — TRADING PSYCHOLOGY & JOURNALING
ICT's Core Psychology Rules
• This is not gambling. Treat it as a business — with a plan and rules.
• Losses are tuition fees. Every losing trade teaches something. Journal it.
• Scared money never makes money. Undercapitalization causes over-trading.
• The best trades feel uncomfortable — they look wrong to everyone else.
• If you are revenge trading after a loss — STOP. Close everything. Walk away.
• Your results are a reflection of your PROCESS, not luck.
• Compare yourself only to who you were last month, not to other traders.
• Demo for 90 days minimum before touching real money.
• Journaling is NOT optional. Without a journal you cannot improve.
• ICT's rule: if you would Tweet about your trade before entering — it's ego, not edge.
Journaling Requirements (ICT Standard)
• Record: Date, Time, Market, Direction (Long/Short), Entry Price, Stop Price, Target Price
• Record: Which session, which macro window, which PD Array was used
• Record: Was liquidity taken before entry? Yes/No
• Record: What was the daily bias? Did the trade align?
• Screenshot: Mark the entry, stop, and target on the chart
• Record: Did I follow my rules? Yes/No
• Record: What did I do wrong? (even on winning trades)
• Weekly review: What patterns appear in my winning trades vs losing trades?
• ICT advice: 'Algorithmic Timing and Journaling' — March 2025 lecture is essential viewing
